{{Use Irish English|date=February 2014}} {{BLP sources|date=May 2011}} {{Infobox person | name = J. P. McManus | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|3|10|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Limerick]], [[Ireland]] | residence = [[Ireland]], [[Switzerland]], [[Barbados]] | occupation = | salary = | networth = {{gain}}€2.1 billion (2018)<ref>https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/rich-list-2018/profiles/jp-mcmanus-36489006.html</ref> | spouse = Noreen McManus | children = 4<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2001/05/05/story2196.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108202443/http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2001/05/05/story2196.asp |archivedate= 8 January 2008 |df= }}</ref> | website = }} '''John Patrick''' "'''J. P.'''" '''McManus''' (born 10 March 1951) is an [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] businessman and racehorse owner.
== Early life == Born in [[Limerick]], [[Ireland]], McManus began his business career at his family's construction plant hire firm, and then became an on-course bookmaker at Limerick's [[Markets Field]] greyhound track. He later moved into horse ownership and punting and laying horses on the advice of his associate Jimmy Hayes.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}
In 1982, he and his wife, Noreen, a former mental health nurse,{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} bought Martinstown Stud on over {{convert|400|acre|km2}} in [[County Limerick]] from the McCalmont family.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} McManus's first horse was Cill Dara, which had been owned by the late Edenderry solicitor and gambler, Tim O'Toole.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} McManus is now [[National Hunt racing]]'s largest owner, with over 100 horses in training.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} In 2006, he built a €20&nbsp;million residence next to Martinstown Stud.<ref>{{cite news|title=Construction starts on JP McManus mansion, mother of all stately homes|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/construction-starts-on-jp-mcmanus-mansion-mother-of-all-stately-homes-26223793.html}}</ref> In 2013, he completed a €150&nbsp;million home in Barbados.<ref>{{cite news |first=Eugene |last=Phelan |title=JP McManus’ €150m Barbados mansion almost complete |url=http://www.limerickleader.ie/news/business/business-news/jp-mcmanus-150m-barbados-mansion-almost-complete-1-5571527 |work=Limerick Leader |publisher=Johnston Publishing |date=10 October 2013 |accessdate=3 January 2014 }}</ref>
== Career == McManus's first Cheltenham Festival winner was a horse called Mister Donovan in 1982.<ref name="Legend">{{cite news|last1=Scott|first1=Brough|title=The stuff of Legend - Independent.ie|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/horse-racing/cheltenham/the-stuff-of-legend-30062555.html|accessdate=19 March 2018|work=Independent.ie|date=8 March 2014|language=en}}</ref> Mister Donovan was the second favourite and won the race after the favourite, Angelo Salvini, whipped around at the start.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} The rider of Angelo Silvani - Alan Brown - rarely ever rode again. McManus's distinctive green-and-gold-hooped racing colours are those of the [[South Liberties GAA Club]], in Co Limerick. {{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}
The most famous{{By whom|date=May 2011}} of his horses is [[Istabraq]], a three-time winner of the [[Champion Hurdle]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Connell|first1=Brian|title=Istabraq is floored again|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/istabraq-is-floored-again-1.305079|accessdate=20 March 2018|work=The Irish Times|date=28 April 2001}}</ref> Twenty time champion jockey [[Tony McCoy]] was retained as his stable jockey for a large part of his career, a role that [[Barry Geraghty]] has taken over since McCoy's retirement.<ref>{{cite news |first=Marcus |last=Townsend |title=Barry Geraghty to replace Tony McCoy as No 1 jockey to leading owner JP McManus.|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/racing/article-3133767/Barry-Geraghty-replace-Tony-McCoy-No-1-jockey-leading-owner-JP-McManus.html |work=Daily Mail |publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd |date=21 June 2015 |accessdate=3 December 2016 }}</ref> Former champion jockey [[Jonjo O'Neill]] trains some of his horses at the Jackdaws Castle facility which McManus owns. He has often appeared at race meetings in recent years with the British actor Clive Owen. McManus was once close to jockeys Ted Walsh (Greasepaint at Fairyhouse one Easter Monday) and Niall Madden, T. Busteed, F. Codd and C. Roche, Micky Flynn and a slew of others. {{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}
McManus's horse [[Don't Push It]], ridden by McCoy and trained by O'Neill, won the 2010 [[Grand National]] Steeplechase.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/horseracing/7575964/Grand-National-2010-Dont-Push-It-is-lucky-15-for-Tony-McCoy-at-Aintree.html|title=Grand National 2010: Don't Push It is lucky 15 for Tony McCoy at Aintree|last=Armytage|first=Marcus|date=10 April 2010|website=The Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|access-date=19 April 2016}}</ref>
In 2012, McManus's horse [[Synchronised (horse)|Synchronised]] won the [[Cheltenham Gold Cup]]. Synchronised went on to run in the 2012 [[John Smiths]] [[Grand National]] with champion jockey [[Tony McCoy]] on 14 April 2012. Synchronised threw McCoy on the way to the starting area; after being caught and veterinary checks were performed, Synchronised was re-entered. However, he fell at [[Becher's Brook]] and sadly broke two legs and had to be put down.<ref>{{cite news |title=Death of Cheltenham Gold Cup winner Synchronised at The Grand National 2012 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/apr/14/synchronised-grand-national |accessdate=15 April 2012 |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News and Media |location=London |first=Greg |last=Wood |date=14 April 2012}}</ref> McManus had his 50th Cheltenham festival winner when [[Buveur d'Air]] won the [[2017 Champion Hurdle]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Grady|first1=Sean|title=JP all smiles as he notches 50th festival winner - Independent.ie|url=https://m.independent.ie/sport/horse-racing/cheltenham/jp-all-smiles-as-he-notches-50th-festival-winner-35532653.html|accessdate=19 March 2018|work=Independent.ie|date=15 March 2017|language=en}}</ref>
== Currency exchange and business == A significant part of McManus' wealth, though not all, appears to have been derived as a private [[Foreign exchange market|foreign exchange]] [[Trader (finance)|trader]], though seasoned traders doubt this very much, which McManus operates from a small office over a jewellery shop in Geneva, Switzerland, his city of official residence.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} McManus also had a permanent suite at London's [[Dorchester Hotel]]{{citation needed|date=November 2014}} for over thirty years and he returns to Ireland regularly. Currencies are apparently his speciality,{{clarify|date=November 2014}} always{{citation needed|date=November 2014}} working on the advice of his good friends [[Dermot Desmond]] and [[Joe Lewis (British businessman)|Joe Lewis]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} He now{{when|date=November 2014}} has a wide portfolio of investments from leisure centres and betting shops to pubs and nursing homes.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}} He is a large shareholder in Ladbrokes.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} McManus appears to have been a holder of Junior Irish bonds at the time of the downturn.
==Sporting interests== Together with business associate [[John Magnier]], McManus built up a 28.89 per cent shareholding in [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], which they sold on to businessman [[Malcolm Glazer]] after falling out with manager [[Alex Ferguson]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} In 2004, McManus began sponsoring the [[Limerick GAA]] teams, choosing to use the non-commercial Sporting Limerick promotional brand on the jerseys.
He is also a keen [[golf]]er and a close friend of [[Tiger Woods]],{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} who married at the [[Sandy Lane (resort)|Sandy Lane Hotel]] in Barbados, which McManus co-owns. The wedding at Sandy Lane was a gift from the owners of Sandy Lane to Woods.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}
McManus routinely competes in [[Pro-Am]] golf events. He is a two-time winner of the [[Alfred Dunhill Links Championship]] pro-am pairs competition,{{citation needed|date=November 2014}} partnering with [[Pádraig Harrington]] on both occasions.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}
==Glackin Report== In 1991, an Irish company law inspector, solicitor John Glackin, was appointed by the Irish Government to investigate complicated dealings involving [[Dermot Desmond]] and the purchase and sale of the former Johnston Mooney and O’Brien site in [[Ballsbridge]], Dublin, to [[Telecom Éireann]]. While Desmond represented himself as an intermediary in the sale, Glackin’s report said Mr Desmond, businessman JP McManus and [[John Magnier]] were beneficiaries of the sale. Mr Desmond strenuously disputed Glackin’s findings.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2011/0323/1224292846891.html | work=The Irish Times | first=Colm | last=Keena | title=Financier is no stranger to business and political rows | date=23 March 2011}}</ref>
According to the Glackin Report,<ref>{{cite web|author=Author Gavin Sheridan |url=http://thestory.ie/2012/01/17/the-glackin-report-complete/ |title=The Glackin Report – complete – |publisher=Thestory.ie |date=17 January 2012 |accessdate=11 April 2017}}</ref> Hoddle Investments (the vehicle through which the deal was handled) executed two contracts with Telecom Éireann for the sale of the Johnston Mooney & O'Brien site for an aggregate price of £9.4&nbsp;million, on 7 May 1990. Glackin concluded that McManus had loaned £1.5&nbsp;million to Chestvale to purchase the site from the liquidator in August 1989. McManus made the investment through an AIB account in Jersey in the name of J&N McMahon. Whether this account was to the benefit of John and Noreen McManus was not confirmed as AIB refused to break client confidentiality.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1993/0708/Pg001.html | work=The Irish Times}}</ref>
The report concluded that McManus was a beneficiary of the sale of the site to Telecom Éireann, and received £500,000 in cash from the transaction, which Dermot Desmond had stored in a tennis holdall in his safe. At paragraph 5.4.4 of the report, Glackin concludes that:
{{Quote|text="I am satisfied, on a basis that I believe is reasonable, that Mr. McManus was promised by Mr. Desmond as his consideration for the advance a share of the profits and that this was either agreed in advance or during the period between 29th June 1990 when the money was received from Telecom, and 19th July 1990 when the request was made to Ansbacher for the first cash withdrawal of £100,000. I can find no evidence that any other person received any of the cash of £500,000 and find accordingly that it was received by Mr. McManus."}}No criminal charges were made against McManus or the other principals involved resulting from the findings of the Glackin Report.
== Wealth == McManus's personal fortune is estimated at €4&nbsp;billion.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} McManus is reputed to have been affected by the economic downturn.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/specials/rich_list/article3800777.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=JP McManus | date=27 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref>
== Charitable contributions == In 1996, McManus established the J. P. McManus Scholarship Award which provides €6,750 each year for third level education to eight selected students at his former secondary school C.B.S. Sexton Street in Limerick.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} Every five years, he organises the J. P. McManus Invitation Pro-Am golf tournament in Limerick to raise funds for Limerick charities.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} He has been awarded an honorary doctorate from the University of Limerick and has funded the new Kemmy Business School at the University. Jim Kemmy was a close friend of McManus's. Kemmy introduced the famous Irish [[tax amnesty]] onto the floor of Dáil Éireann.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} In July 2012, McManus donated over €1&nbsp;million to the Daughters of Charity foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.limerickleader.ie/community/community-news/latest-news/jp-donates-over-1m-to-daughters-of-charity-in-limerick-1-4105121|title=Profile: JP donates over €1m to Daughters of Charity in Limerick|publisher=Limerick Leader|accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref> He has donated land money and horses to the st Josephs Foundation to help build Liskennett Farm Equine Therapy Centre,Limerick for adults and children with autism.
== Gambling == McManus won millions{{clarify|date=June 2014}} from gamblers [[Terry Ramsden]] and the late Robert Sangster by laying horses.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} He says he "rarely bets" these days and when he does he usually describes them as "little bets".{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} He says betting is "not an obsession".{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} In 2012, he won $17.4m gambling in the United States, of which $5.2m was retained as [[income tax]] by the US [[Internal Revenue Service]] (IRS).<ref name="it2543096"/> In 2016, ''[[The Irish Times]]'' reported that he was seeking a refund of the tax on the basis of the US [[double taxation treaty]] with Ireland; the IRS stated that McManus was a self-confessed tax exile out of Ireland and therefore - despite McManus's sworn affidavits to the contrary - not a [[legal resident]] of Ireland in 2012.<ref name="it2543096">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/us-insists-jp-mcmanus-not-irish-resident-when-over-17m-won-1.2543096|title=US insists JP McManus not Irish resident when over $17m won|last=Keena|first=Colm|date=22 February 2016|work=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref>
== Health == McManus was diagnosed with cancer in late 2008 and after receiving treatment in the United States, he is said to be recovering.<ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Lavery – 24 April 2009 12:00 PM |url=http://www.herald.ie/national-news/jp-mcmanus-fights-cancer-in-us-clinic-1718899.html |title=JP McManus fights cancer in US clinic |publisher=Herald.ie |date=24 April 2009 |accessdate=11 April 2017}}</ref>
